                  </persName>
               
            .</p>
               <p>MR. LEE conducted the prosecution.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18291029-238-person1931">
                  HENRY 
                  FRANCIS PIAGET
               <interp inst="t18291029-238-person1931" type="surname" value="FRANCIS PIAGET"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-238-person1931" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18291029-238-person1931" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I <rs id="t18291029-238-viclabel1346" type="occupation">keep a circulating library and a tobaconist's shop</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18291029-238-victim1930 t18291029-238-viclabel1346"></join> - the prisoner was my <rs id="t18291029-238-deflabel1347" type="occupation">servant</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18291029-238-defend1928 t18291029-238-deflabel1347"></join>. On Friday evening, the 16th of October, I went to my tea-caddy and found the prisoner's hat on it - I took it off and felt it was very heavy; I lifted up his handkerchief, which was in it, and found a phosphorus-box and a newspaper - I sent him up stairs, and called in a person who saw what was in it, and we sent for Mr. Clark; in about half an hour we searched his box, which he opened himself, and found in it one phosphorus-box, two snuff-boxes, two snuff-canisters, and a book, which are mine - these are the articles.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. COLLVER. Q. The prisoner expressed no reluctance to open his box? A. No; he did it by order of Mrs. Clark, his mistress - he is not my apprentice.(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>JOHN CLARK. I was in the shop while they went up stairs to open the box; the prisoner said he did not know how he came by the things; he knew they were Mr. Piaget's.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined. Q. Had you said any thing to him about being prosecuted? A. No; I told him as I had found him out in so many things, I would certainly go to the full extent of the law; he was apprenticed to me, but used to do a few things for the prosecutor, who is single; he has been a good boy till lately, when he has got some bad companions.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18291029-238-person1932">
                  EDWARD 
                  PAYNE
               <interp inst="t18291029-238-person1932" type="surname" value="PAYNE"></interp>
